[1] India (West Bengal)
Date: Tue, 30 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Statesman News Service, 30 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.thestatesman.net/page.news.php?clid=23&theme=&usrsess=1&id=88299>

After catching Kolkata [formerly Calcutta] [unprepared], dengue has now spread
to several district towns. In Salt Lake, 10 people have been affected. Health
officials fear that in the next 15-20 days the disease may create havoc in the
districts. Mr K K Bagchi, the health secretary, said that about 300 people are
affected and a total of 11 people have died of dengue.
The majority of the deceased and infected are from Kolkata. However, he
admitted that a number of people from the district towns have tested zero-
positive [i.e. show antibody evidence of having been infected - Mod.JW]. The
figure provided by the health authorities clearly suggests that the disease is
now getting a grip in the districts.
The number of affected people in the districts is 60-65. The breakdown is:
Salt Lake 10-24; Parganas (North) 20 to 25; Hooghly and Howrah 10 each; South
Parganas 5-6, and Nadia, Burdwan, Birbhum, Murshidabad one each.
Officials [fear] that carriers of the virus would migrate to nearby district
towns and the number of affected would increase in the next 2 weeks.
The health secretary said that World Health Organization's guidelines for the
treatment of the dengue-affected has been supplied to all the state hospitals
and nursing homes to make them familiar with proper treatment.
Authorities also said that Mac Elisa [ELISA] test kits have been sent to all 4
district medical colleges so that dengue confirmation tests can be carried out
there. This will speed up the time required to bring samples and undergo the
confirmation test at School of Tropical Medicine or at NICED.
The Purulia CMOH [Chief Medical Officer of Health], Dr Bhujanga Bhusan Patra,
confirmed today that [3 children 16 years old and under], all from Purulia
district, died of dengue in the past 2 days. Officials also confirmed that 24
more people were suffering from the disease in the district, Statesman News
Service adds from Purulia. Mr Bikash Bhattacharya, the mayor, Kolkata
Municipal Corporation, said that the [use of] mosquito-repellant spray and the
anti-dengue campaign would continue until December 2005, as the corporation
doesn't want to take chances.
--
