[2] India (New Delhi)
Date: Fri, 26 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhuanet, 26 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-08/26/content_3407606.htm>

The Indian capital Delhi reported 26 mosquito-borne dengue cases with 3 deaths
in the past 2 weeks, Indo-Asian News Service reported Friday.
Out of the 26 cases, 14 were reported from west Delhi, the city government
said.
2 of the 3 that died of dengue came from other places, one from neighboring
Uttar Pradesh and another from southeast India's Andhra Pradesh.
N.K. Yadav, deputy health officer of the Municipal Corporation of Delhi (MCD),
said the situation is under control and they are taking all precautions.
So far in 2005 the government has identified 10 326 houses as [sites of
mosquito breeding], compared with some 7000 last year [2004]. And more than
5400 house owners have been prosecuted this year compared to 2035 last year.
The authorities have slapped a fine of 500 rupees (11.49 US dollars) each on
negligent house owners and have decided to fine 2000 rupees (45.98 US dollars)
for repeated offences.
"We have hired 1055 extra workers to help our regular 2500 health workers to
search the houses where mosquito breeding is taking place," he said.
--
