[3] India (Calcutta/Kolkata)
Date: Wed, 24 Aug 2005 03:13:43 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Kolkata News line, Cities.epressindia.com, 23 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=145260>

The Kolkata [formerly Calcutta] Municipal Corporation (KMC) figures [differ]
from [those of] the government. While the state health department claims that
4 persons have so far died of dengue, according to an official KMC statement,
only one death has been confirmed. However, this figure has turned out to be
erroneous -- the person said to be dead in the KMC statement is presently
recovering from the disease.
According to a statement issued earlier by member, mayor-in-council (health)
Subodh Dey, a resident of Mahatma Gandhi Road died of dengue yesterday. This
was the only death confirmed by the KMC till Monday.
But the 28-year-old patient in question was found to be recovering at the ICCU
of Apollo Gleneagles Hospital today. "He is far from [being] dead. I attended
to him 5 minutes back, and he is feeling much better than on Monday," said the
attending nurse late this evening..
The basis of "detection" of the number of dengue cases in the city is also
extremely ambiguous. The KMC has set up a health camp at Prince Anwar Shah
Road to conduct blood tests on the hundreds of patients complaining of fever
in wards 93 and 94. The doctor in charge, Amitava Chatterjee, said, "We are
conducting [only] malaria detection tests. We do not have the capability to
detect cases of dengue. Blood samples are taken from us by NICED (National
Institute of Cholera and Enteric Diseases) and dengue tests are conducted.
This takes about a week.
In the last 2 days, NICED has taken 30 blood samples from this camp".
According to the camp's register, out of 196 people who visited the camp in
the last 2 days, a total of 147 had undergone blood tests. However, only 30 of
these samples have been submitted to NICED. The question is: Why have only a
few samples been submitted to NICED?
Meanwhile, residents of the area are complaining that the outbreak of fever
has been due to the KMC's neglect of sanitary conditions. "Since no toilets
have been provided in the area by the KMC, we have dug several pits next to
our homes," said [one man], whose 20-year-old wife died of suspected dengue.
"Once a pit gets filled, we dig another one," he added. There are 20 such pits
now, and these are areas from which swarms of mosquitos originate.
[Byline: Sagnik Chowdhury]
[ProMED medical entomology moderator Mike Service is away at a conference, but
my understanding is that although the dengue vector _Aedes aegypti_ will breed
in polluted water, it draws the line at toilets. - Mod.JW]
