[7] St Lucia
Date: Fri, 26 Aug 2005
From: Shirley Bannatyne <shirley.bannatyne@masta.org>
Source: Caribbean Media Corporation news agency website. 17 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.cananews.com>

Health authorities in St Lucia have placed the island on a dengue alert
following an outbreak of the disease on the neighbouring French island of
Martinique [see (10) below].
Chief Medical Officer Dr Stephen King said the outbreak of dengue has become a
source of concern, with the number of cases being reported to medical
authorities in the recent past.
Martinique has already confirmed 3 cases of the virus, and Dr. King said the
disease could easily reach neighbouring shores with great potential for
spreading.
"Whenever there is an outbreak [in a place frequently visited by travelers,]
it is easy for people to come back and cause an outbreak in their country of
origin, so we need to be very vigilant," he said.
He said that every year the island needs to go on the alert for dengue, but
more so in this period, given the fact that Martinique has reported an
outbreak of the dengue virus type 4.
"We are not saying that St Lucians should cease all travel to Martinique, but
those going there need to be aware of the clear and present danger of being
infected," he said.
St Lucia has recorded 2 major outbreaks of dengue fever with the most recent
being in 2002.
The Ministry of Health has been advising persons against the indiscriminate
disposal of garbage in drains and ravines in an effort to avoid potential
breeding grounds for mosquitoes.
The department has also urged persons experiencing high fevers associated with
headaches and joint pains to seek immediate medical attention.
"We have a surveillance system in place, so that anyone with these symptoms
needs to seek immediate medical attention, and we would want that report to
get to the Ministry so we can implement our control measures," Dr. King said.
--
