[8] Singapore
Date: Wed, 25 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhuanet, 24 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-08/24/content_3398559.htm>

A total of 7403 dengue fever cases have been reported in Singapore during the
first 8 months of [2005], Channel NewsAsia report said on Wednesday.
The number for the corresponding period of [2004] was 3782.
The city-state has seen an upward trend in the number of [cases of] the
disease in recent years, with a total of 9459 cases being found last year
[2004], almost doubling the 4788 cases in 2003.
To tackle the problem, the National Environment Agency (NEA) has allocated
another 7.5 million Singapore dollars (about 4.5 million US dollars) to flush
the drains, adding to the yearly 2.5 million Singapore dollars (about 1.5
million US dollars).
Drains, pump rooms and water tanks, as well as flower vases, plant pot plates
and watering cans at home are identified as the most likely mosquito breeding
sources.
Having hired some 360 field inspectors so far, up from 110 last year, the NEA
will recruit 150 more in the next 2 months and urge town councils to hire
dedicated pest control operators to do more flushing of the drains, fogging
and clearing of the breeding sites.
Last month [July 2005], the agency announced that it would put up posters at
bus stops and Mass Rapid Transit (MRT) stations, as well as distributing new
sets of dengue educational kits to 70 000 families, to strengthen its
prevention measures.
--
