[9] Mexico
Date: Mon, Aug 29 2005
From: Jose Miguel Pickering Lopez <pickering_lopez@yahoo.com.mx>
Source: El Universal, Mexico, 26 Aug 2005 [translated by Alfonso J. Rodriguez]
[edited]
<http://estadis.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/58491.html>

Dengue fever figures reported for this year in Quintana Roo exceed by 200
percent the number of cases detected in 2004; consequently, health authorities
started emergency programs for land and air insecticide spraying, as well as
placing Abate in water tanks and promoting the "clean yards" campaign.
Jose Joaquin Calderon-Martinez, state director of health services, announced
that by epidemiological week No. 32, they have reported 336 cases of dengue
fever.
250 of the cases correspond to the classic form and 86 are dengue hemorrhagic
fever; these figures exceed by far the number of cases reported for the same
time in 2004, when the total number of cases was 139, 113 with classic dengue
fever and 26 with dengue hemorrhagic fever.
[City] councils with the greatest numbers of dengue fever cases are Othon P.
Blanco (210 cases), Benito Juarez (100 cases), and Felipe Carrillo-Puerto (18
cases). The remaining communities report 1-2 cases.
"The objective is to reduce mosquito proliferation, especially since Mexico
City is surrounded by an 80-hectare savannah, well-suited to larvae breeding",
affirmed Mr. Calderon-Martinez.
After Hurricane Emily, which hit the area on 18 Jul 2005, health authorities
received funds from Fonden [Mexico's Fund for Natural Disasters] for an
emergency program aiming to control and combat dengue, specifically for
fumigating actions all over the state and placing Abate in household water
tanks.
In Tamaulipas, 928 cases of dengue fever and 129 cases of dengue hemorrhagic
fever have been reported. The State Health Secretariat intensified actions for
fighting the mosquito vector, through aerial fumigation actions in the most
affected areas and land brigades in 11 city councils.
The dengue outbreak in Tamaulipas urged the Government of Nuevo Leon to
initiate a program for vehicle fumigation in the border areas between the 2
states.
Subsecretary for Disease Prevention and Control from Nuevo Leon Health
Secretariat, Mr. Ricardo Huerta-Gallega, [stated in a telephone interview]
that in the first 2 days of this campaign, 2091 fumigations have been
performed in a similar number of vehicles: 1401 in private cars, 612 in
trucks, and 78 in buses.
During the current epidemiological week [3rd week August 2005], 1135 dengue
fever cases were diagnosed; 69 (6.1 percent) of them were dengue hemorrhagic
fever cases. The ratio of dengue fever to dengue hemorrhagic fever of 15:1.
Cumulative case figures for the year [2005] are 20 323 cases, of which 6.3
percent (1278 cases) are of the hemorrhagic form, with the ratio of dengue
fever to dengue hemorrhagic fever of 15:1. The cumulative morbidity rate is
76.5 per 100 000 inhabitants.
Circulating serotypes are 1 and 3. The cumulative case toll for the period
increased by 1.9 percent as compared to the total cumulative number of cases
by the same date [3rd week August] last year [2004].
In the current epidemiological week [3rd week August 2005], no deaths from
dengue have been reported.
A 2.3 percent increase in the number of cases as compared to last week [2nd
week August 2005] was reported, so the situation is considered to be an
epidemic.
52 percent of reported cases are in the less-than-15-year-old age group; 21.5
percent of cases are in the 15-to-24-year-old age group. Federal areas that
reported the highest case tolls are: Carabobo (240), Apure (144), Mida (135),
Barinas (89), and Thira (77).
--
