[10] Guadeloupe and Martinique (French Antilles)
Date: Tue, 30 Aug 2005
From: Thomas Roesel <Thomas.Roesel@na.amedd.army.mil>
Source: Invs.sante.fr, 25 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/display/?
doc=3Dpresse/2005/le_point_sur/dengue_250805/index.html>

Situation in the French Antilles [as of 25 Aug 2005]
Guadeloupe
----------
Since June 2005, the available dengue epidemiological surveillance data reveal
a steady increase in the number of cases reported each week.
Epidemic onset was identified as the beginning of July, after the daily
epidemic threshold of suspected dengue cases had been exceeded for 2
consecutive weeks, as determined by the sentinel physician network.
Between 1 Jun and 24 Aug 2005, the network of city sentinel physicians
reported 331 suspected clinical cases. Among the 403 diagnostic requests
prescribed by island physicians, 183 cases had been confirmed by biological
analyses.
The serotypes DEN-3 and DEN-4 had been identified. The communities most
affected were those in the south of Basse-Terre, as well as those on St.
Martin island. During the past 2 weeks, extension has begun into communities
adjoining the initial sites (Basse-Terre, Gourbeyre, Saint-Claude and Baillif)
and, to a lesser degree, into the communities of northern Basse Terre (Pointe
Noire) and on Grande Terre (Abymes, Gosier, Sainte-Anne, Morne l'eau).
Martinique
----------
The threshold for the seasonal recurrence of dengue was reached in mid-June
[2005], earlier than is normal, and the epidemic threshold had been exceeded
by mid-July 2005. Between 1 Jun and 24 Aug 2005, the network of sentinel city
physicians reported 405 suspected cased of dengue.
Among the 845 diagnostic requests prescribed by island physicians, 350 cases
had been confirmed by biological analyses (serology and by reverse
transcriptase PCR).
This epidemic is linked to co-circulation of serotypes DEN-2 and DEN-4. The
latter predominates and represents 70 percent of the actual isolates from 2005
(from the 58 serotypes detected since January 2005, there are 41 DEN-4, 16 DEN-
2, and only one DEN-3).
Extrapolating from the sentinel network data, one can estimate that, since the
beginning of the epidemic, between 1500 and 2000 people have been infected in
Martinique.
The serotypes DEN-2 and DEN-4 have been identified. The communities most
affected are centrally located (Fort de France, Lamentin, Saint-Joseph, and
Schoelcher), certain localities in the south (Riviere Pilote, Marin, and
Francois) and north (Trinite and Basse Pointe).
Even though it is difficult to foresee the magnitude of this epidemic in terms
of the number of infected individuals, [considering] the evolutionary duration
and geographical extension, the types of circulating viruses and the current
climatic conditions are favorable for continued development and expansion in
both departments (Guadeloupe and Martinique).
--
Thomas Roesel, MD, PhD, FACP
<Thomas.Roesel@na.amedd.army.mil>
[Elsevier on-line reference:
Hales S, van Panhuis W. A new strategy for dengue control. 12 Feb 2005, The
Lancet, 365 (9459): 551-552
<http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140673605179227/fulltext
>
